


'''Amy Elizabeth Greene''' (Born October, 2, 1975 in Morristown, Tenn.) is an American novelist. Her   debut novel ''Bloodroot'' was a national bestseller. Her second novel ''Long Man'' qs published in March of 2014  <ref>{{cite web|title=RH|url=http://www.rhspeakers.com/speaker/amy-greene/}}</ref>  and a contributor to the ''New York Times'' among other publications.

== Biography ==

Greene was born Amy Elizabeth Oler in Morristown, Tenn, and grew up in Whitesburg, Tenn. in the foothills of the Great Smokey Mountains. She received a Bachelor's Degree from [[Vermont College]] in 2008. In 2011 she was awarded the Weatherford Award for Fiction at Berea College.

== Writing ==

Greene's first novel, ''Bloodroot'', was published in 2010. It was a New York Times and national bestseller, garnering praise from such publications as USA Today, The New York Times, The Boston Globe and The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. Bloodroot received an "A" from ''Entertainment Weekly''<ref>{{cite web|title=EW|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20337910,00.html}}</ref> and appeared on their "Must List.<ref>{{cite web|title=EW2|publisher=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20338353,00.html}}</ref>" It received a starred review in ''Booklist<ref>{{cite web|title=Booklist|url=http://www.booklistonline.com/ProductInfo.aspx?pid=3749284&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1}}</ref>'' and ''Kirkus Reviews,'' was recognized on Amazon.com's Best Debut Fiction list<ref>{{cite web|title=Amazon1|url=http://www.amazon.com/gp/feature.html/ref=amb_link_354383582_10?ie=UTF8&plgroup=1&docId=1000628051&pf_rd_m=ATVPDKIKX0DER&pf_rd_s=left-1&pf_rd_r=1MZEVSR7Q7K9VYJB6V3S&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_p=1279095702&pf_rd_i=2486012011}}</ref> and was one of Amazon.com's Best Books of 2010<ref>{{cite web|title=AZ2|url=http://www.amazon.com/gp/feature.html/ref=br_lf_m_1000626091_pglink_next?ie=UTF8&docId=1000626091&plgroup=1&plpage=2}}</ref>. ''Bloodroot'' was a ''New York Times'' Editor's Choice<ref>{{cite web|title=NYT1|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/21/books/review/EdChoice-t.html}}</ref> and made the ''Indie Next List'' before it's debut. Greene won the Weatherford Award in 2010<ref>{{cite web|title=WA|url=http://www.berea.edu/appalachian-center/weatherford-award/past-winners/}}</ref> and was named 2010 Tennessee Writer of the Year<ref>{{cite web|title=TWA|url=http://tn-writers.org/awards/tennessee-writer-of-the-year/}}</ref>. ''Bloodroot'' has been published in Italy and Turkey. According to WorldCat, the book is held in 1292 libraries <ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/bloodroot-a-novel/oclc/326532333&referer=brief_results  WorldCat item record]</ref>
Greene's second novel ''Long Man'' was published in March of 2014.<ref name=wcLM>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/long-man-a-novel/oclc/846846817&referer=brief_results   WorldCat item record]</ref>   and as of July 2014 is in 710 libraries according to worldCat.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/long-man-a-novel/oclc/846846817&referer=brief_results  WorldCat book listing]</ref>
== Personal Life ==

Greene married her husband, Adam Greene, in 1994. They have two children.

== Works ==

2010, "Bloodroot" - Novel, published by Alfred A. Knopf

2014, "Long Man," - Novel, published by Alfred A. Knopf

